# Reference accessed: 2026-05-31 via gh api.
#
# emqtt is the **MQTT 5.0 client (CLI + Erlang lib)**
# from EMQX â€” connects to MQTT brokers as publisher,
# subscriber, or raw connection.  Pivots from R291 Lem
# (Common Lisp `command-line-arguments`) into the
# **Erlang language tooling cluster**.  Sister tools:
# rebar3 (Erlang build), kerl (Erlang version manager),
# relx (Erlang release), elvis (Erlang linter).
# **MAJOR MILESTONE**: corpus's **first documented
# Erlang `getopt:parse`-based CLI** â€” adds Erlang
# `jcomellas/getopt` to the cross-language CLI taxonomy
# (31 library variants now).
#
# Critical extraction note: emqtt uses **Erlang
# `getopt:parse` library** at src/emqtt_cli.erl:123/127/
# 132 â€” `jcomellas/getopt` is the de-facto standard
# Erlang getopt library used by rebar/rebar3/elvis/sup/
# aefate/weatherreport.  Different from BEAM stdlib
# `init:get_argument` (low-level Erlang start args) and
# different from Elixir's `OptionParser`.  Each option
# spec is a 5-tuple: `{Name :: atom(), Short ::
# char() | undefined, Long :: string() | undefined,
# ArgSpec :: undefined | atom() | {atom(), Default},
# HelpString :: string()}`.  ArgSpec atom controls
# typed parsing (integer | string | boolean | atom).
# Documents the **5-tuple option-spec pattern** â€”
# distinct from R290 Racket's macro-based DSL and from
# R291 Common Lisp's plist `(:type X :optional t)`.
# Corpus's **first documented Erlang getopt:parse CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: emqtt uses **Erlang module-
# attribute MACROS for spec composition** at src/
# emqtt_cli.erl:26/31/52/95/97/110 â€” `-define(NAME,
# Expr).` creates compile-time MACROS, then `?NAME`
# expands them.  CONNECT_OPTS/PUB_OPTS/SUB_OPTS are
# built via `?CONN_SHORT_OPTS ++ ?HELP_OPT ++
# ?CONN_LONG_OPTS ++ [pub-only-extra-opts]` â€” COMPILE-
# TIME LIST CONCATENATION via `++`.  Documents the
# **compile-time macro-composed CLI spec pattern** â€”
# distinct from R290 Racket macro DSL (`multi-command-
# line`), R278 Scala decline's `Command(...)` runtime
# composition, and R276 picocli inheritance via
# `@Command(subcommands = ...)`.  Plus the pub-only
# extras are SPLICED IN at the end (after long opts)
# â€” `++ [{payload, ...}, ...]`.  Corpus's **first
# documented compile-time macro-concat CLI spec**.
#
# Critical extraction note: emqtt uses **typed
# ArgSpec atoms** at src/emqtt_cli.erl:32-93 â€” each
# option's 4th tuple element is the type discriminator:
#   - `{string, "localhost"}` â†’ string with default
#     "localhost" (host)
#   - `integer` â†’ integer, no default (port)
#   - `{integer, 300}` â†’ integer with default 300
#     (keepalive)
#   - `{atom, 'v5'}` â†’ atom (Erlang symbol) with default
#     'v5' (protocol_version)
#   - `{boolean, false}` â†’ boolean with default false
#     (will-retain, enable-ssl, verify, etc.)
#   - `boolean` (no default) â†’ required boolean (help)
#   - `string` (no default) â†’ required string (iface,
#     username, password, cafile, cert, key, sni)
# Documents the **typed-with-default tuple pattern** â€”
# distinct from R289 D `std.getopt`'s lambda-callback,
# R288 Zig std.process.argsAlloc's manual parsing, and
# R287 Nim parseopt's untyped string returns.  In
# Erlang's `getopt:parse`, the type discriminator is
# DATA (tuple), not a generic type parameter or
# annotation.  Corpus's **first documented typed-atom
# CLI discriminator** in the language taxonomy.
#
# Critical extraction note: emqtt uses **Erlang
# character literals `$h` `$p` `$I` `$V` etc.** at src/
# emqtt_cli.erl:32-93 â€” `$X` syntax is the Erlang
# character literal (integer codepoint).  `$h` is 104
# (the integer value of 'h'), not a string.  Sister
# to R291 Common Lisp `#\h` (CL character literal)
# and distinct from R281 Perl `'h|help'` pipe syntax.
# Two character-literal CLI cluster languages now:
# Erlang `$X`, Common Lisp `#\X` â€” both BEAM/Lisp
# heritage (different families though).  Corpus's
# **second character-literal CLI flag pattern** (after
# CL).
#
# Critical extraction note: emqtt uses **subcommand
# dispatch via pattern-matching on Erlang list head**
# at src/emqtt_cli.erl:122/126/131 â€” `main(["connect" |
# Argv]) -> ...` uses Erlang's cons-cell pattern `[H |
# T]` to destructure the argv list.  The string "connect"
# matches the first element; remaining args go to Argv,
# then passed to `getopt:parse(?CONNECT_OPTS, Argv)`.
# Three subcommand clauses + fallback `main(_Argv) ->
# io:format("Usage: ...")`.  Documents the **cons-cell
# subcommand dispatch pattern** â€” distinct from R290
# Racket's `multi-command-line #:subcommands` macro
# (declarative), R278 Scala decline `Opts.subcommand`
# (combinator), and R276 picocli `@Command(subcommands
# = {...})` (annotation array).  Erlang's approach uses
# RUNTIME PATTERN MATCHING â€” the dispatch is a normal
# function-clause match, not a special CLI construct.
# Corpus's **first documented cons-cell subcommand
# dispatch**.
#
# Critical extraction note: emqtt uses **runtime
# mutex-style validation** at src/emqtt_cli.erl:137-142
# for `pub` subcommand â€” `{Payload, File}` case
# expression: `{undefined, undefined} -> log_halt(
# "Error: missing --payload or --file~n", [])` â€” the
# pub subcommand REQUIRES one of --payload or --file
# (XOR-ish: not really mutex but mutually-required).
# Documents the **runtime mutually-required pattern**
# â€” convergent with R291 Lem's runtime tcp+stdio mutex
# (mutually-exclusive variant) and R252 saya
# (mutex-via-clap-builder).  Three rounds now showing
# **runtime cross-flag validation when library lacks
# declarative support**: R252 saya (clap manual),
# R291 Lem (CL `when (and tcp stdio)`), R292 emqtt
# (Erlang case `{undefined, undefined}`).  Corpus's
# **third runtime cross-flag validation pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: emqtt uses **DSL inheritance
# via macro concat** for sub/pub spec extension at src/
# emqtt_cli.erl:97/110 â€” both PUB_OPTS and SUB_OPTS
# start with `?CONN_SHORT_OPTS` (the 8 conn opts), add
# their own command-specific opts (`topic`/`qos`/
# `retain` for pub, `topic`/`qos` for sub), then add
# `?HELP_OPT ++ ?CONN_LONG_OPTS` (help + 15 conn long
# opts), THEN add command-specific long opts (`payload`
# /`file`/`repeat`/`repeat_delay` for pub, `retain-as-
# publish`/`retain-handling`/`print` for sub).
# Documents the **interleaved spec composition
# pattern** â€” short â†’ cmd-specific short â†’ help â†’ long
# â†’ cmd-specific long.  This ORDERING controls help
# output ordering when `getopt:usage` is called.
# Distinct from R290 Racket subcommand isolation
# (each subcommand its own spec) and R276 picocli
# `@Mixin` (orthogonal mixins).
#
# Hunt-skip notes: skipped `_elvis` (already in corpus
# at more_src/_elvis), `_rebar3` (corpus + brew stock),
# `_rebar` (brew stock), `_sup` (blacklisted), `_relx`
# (blacklisted), `_kerl` (corpus + blacklisted).
# Probed jcomellas/getopt examples (too generic, not a
# real CLI), basho/rebar (deprecated Erlang build),
# 2600hz/kazoo `core/sup/src/sup.erl` (Kazoo internal
# tool, blacklisted as sup), aeternity/aefate (FATE VM
# inspector, niche), apache/couchdb weatherreport
# (CouchDB diagnostic, namespace conflict with
# weatherreport gem).  Chose emqtt: well-known MQTT
# tool, three clear subcommands, rich getopt:parse
# spec with all type variants represented (string/
# integer/boolean/atom with-and-without defaults).

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1

# Shared connection options (CONN_SHORT_OPTS +
# CONN_LONG_OPTS, decoded from emqtt_cli.erl:31-93).
# These 23 opts are common to all three subcommands.
local -a conn_opts
conn_opts=(
  '(-h --host)'{-h,--host}'=[mqtt server hostname or IP address (default: localhost)]:host:_hosts'
  '(-p --port)'{-p,--port}'=[mqtt server port number]:port:'
  '(-I --iface)'{-I,--iface}'=[specify the network interface or ip address to use]:iface:'
  '(-V --protocol-version)'{-V,--protocol-version}'=[mqtt protocol version (default: v5)]:version:(v3.1 v3.1.1 v5)'
  '(-u --username)'{-u,--username}'=[username for connecting to server]:username:'
  '(-P --password)'{-P,--password}'=[password for connecting to server]:password:'
  '(-C --clientid)'{-C,--clientid}'=[client identifier]:clientid:'
  '(-k --keepalive)'{-k,--keepalive}'=[keep alive in seconds (default: 300)]:seconds:'
  '--max-inflight=[maximum number of unacked QoS>0 messages in-flight (default: infinity)]:n:'
  '--will-topic=[topic for will message]:topic:'
  '--will-payload=[payload in will message]:payload:'
  '--will-qos=[QoS for will message (default: 0)]:qos:(0 1 2)'
  '--will-retain=[retain in will message (default: false)]:bool:(true false)'
  '--enable-websocket=[enable websocket transport (default: false)]:bool:(true false)'
  '--enable-quic=[enable quic transport (default: false)]:bool:(true false)'
  '--enable-ssl=[enable ssl/tls (default: false)]:bool:(true false)'
  '--tls-version=[TLS protocol version (default: tlsv1.2)]:version:(tlsv1.2 tlsv1.3)'
  '--CAfile=[path to a file containing pem-encoded ca certificates]:file:_files'
  '--cert=[path to a file containing the user certificate in pem format]:file:_files'
  '--key=[path to the file containing the private pem-encoded key]:file:_files'
  '--sni=[server name indication (applies when --enable-ssl)]:sni:'
  '--verify=[TLS verify option (default: false)]:bool:(true false)'
  '--log-level=[log level (default: warning)]:level:(debug info warning error)'
  '--help[help information]'
)

_arguments -C \
  '1: :->subcommand' \
  '*:: :->args' && ret=0

case $state in
  subcommand)
    # Three subcommands from emqtt_cli.erl:122/126/131
    # main/1 clauses + line 146 usage banner.
    local -a subcmds
    subcmds=(
      'connect:open an MQTT connection and keep it alive'
      'pub:publish a message to an MQTT topic'
      'sub:subscribe to an MQTT topic and receive messages'
    )
    _describe -t commands 'emqtt subcommand' subcmds && ret=0
    ;;
  args)
    case $line[1] in
      connect)
        # CONNECT_OPTS = CONN_SHORT + HELP + CONN_LONG
        # (emqtt_cli.erl:95) â€” no additional opts.
        _arguments -s -S $conn_opts && ret=0
        ;;
      pub)
        # PUB_OPTS adds 7 pub-only opts on top of
        # conn opts (emqtt_cli.erl:97-108).  Note:
        # --payload XOR --file required (runtime check
        # at emqtt_cli.erl:137-142).
        _arguments -s -S $conn_opts \
          '(-t --topic)'{-t,--topic}'=[mqtt topic on which to publish (REQUIRED)]:topic:' \
          '(-q --qos)'{-q,--qos}'=[qos level for delivery (default: 0)]:qos:(0 1 2)' \
          '(-r --retain)'{-r,--retain}'=[retain message (default: false)]:bool:(true false)' \
          '--payload=[application message that is being published]:payload:' \
          '--file=[file content to publish]:file:_files' \
          '--repeat=[number of times the message will be repeatedly published (default: 1)]:n:' \
          '--repeat-delay=[seconds to wait between repeated publishes (default: 0)]:seconds:' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
      sub)
        # SUB_OPTS adds 5 sub-only opts on top of conn
        # opts (emqtt_cli.erl:110-120).
        _arguments -s -S $conn_opts \
          '(-t --topic)'{-t,--topic}'=[mqtt topic to subscribe to (REQUIRED)]:topic:' \
          '(-q --qos)'{-q,--qos}'=[maximum qos level for subscription (default: 0)]:qos:(0 1 2)' \
          '--retain-as-publish=[retain-as-publish subscription option (default: false)]:bool:(true false)' \
          '--retain-handling=[retain handling subscription option (default: 0)]:n:(0 1 2)' \
          '--print=[print payload (size: byte count; as-string: render as string)]:mode:(size as-string)' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
    esac
    ;;
esac

return ret
